  "editorial": {
    "title": "Unlocking the Optimal Solution for Sum of Subarray Ranges",
    "intuition": "The problem requires finding the sum of the ranges of all possible subarrays within a given array. A range is defined as the difference between the maximum and minimum values in a subarray. The brute force approach, although correct, is slow due to its quadratic time complexity, O(n^2), stemming from the nested iteration over the array to consider all subarrays.",
    "bruteForce": "The brute force solution iterates over the array with two nested loops to generate all possible subarrays. For each subarray, it finds the maximum and minimum values and calculates their difference, adding it to the total sum. This approach is straightforward but inefficient for large inputs due to its O(n^2) time complexity and O(1) space complexity.",
    "betterSolution": "A more efficient approach leverages the concept of monotonic stacks or similar data structures to track the maximum and minimum values more efficiently. However, a stack-based solution might not directly apply here as we need the sum of ranges, not just the maximum/minimum values.",
    "optimalSolution": "The optimal solution involves using a single pass through the array while maintaining two arrays (or vectors) to keep track of the next greater and smaller elements for each element. This allows calculating the contribution of each element to the total sum as a maximum or minimum in O(1) time, effectively reducing the time complexity to O(n).",
    "proofOfCorrectness": "The correctness of the optimal solution hinges on the observation that each element's contribution to the total sum can be determined by its role as a maximum or minimum in subarrays. By efficiently identifying the next greater and smaller elements for each element, we accurately compute its contribution to the sum of ranges without needing to explicitly iterate over all subarrays.",
    "dryRun": "Testing with an example array [1, 2, 3] helps validate the approach. The subarrays and their ranges are: [1] (0), [2] (0), [3] (0), [1, 2] (1), [2, 3] (1), [1, 2, 3] (2). The sum of ranges is 0 + 0 + 0 + 1 + 1 + 2 = 4.",
